election_record.label: Vermont 1814 U.S. House of Representatives

overview.note: The Vermont Mirror (Middlebury, VT), Spooner's Vermont Journal (Windsor, VT), The Washingtonian (Windsor, VT) use the spelling Jewett for Luther Jewitt.

The Watchman (Montpelier, VT), October 20, The Washingtonian (Windsor, VT), October 24, The Vermont Mirror (Middlebury, VT), October 26, and Spooner's Vermont Journal (Windsor, VT), October 22, report 17725 votes for Chauncey Langdon, 17718 votes for Asa Lyon, 17719 votes for Charles Marsh, 17716 votes for Daniel Chipman, 17598 votes for John Noyes, 17665 votes for Luther Jewitt, 16975 votes for Ezra Butler, 16974 votes for Richard Skinner, 16948 votes for William C. Bradley, 16969 votes for James Fisk, 16957 votes for William Strong and 16874 votes for Charles Rich.

Columbian Centinel. Massachusetts Federalist (Boston, MA), October 29, reports 17725 votes for Chauncey Langdon, 17718 votes for Asa Lyon, 17719 votes for Charles Marsh, 17716 votes for Daniel Chipman, 17598 votes for John Noyes, 17665 votes for Luther Jewitt, 16975 votes for Ezra Butler, 16974 votes for Richard Skinner, 16938 votes for William C. Bradley, 16969 votes for James Fisk, 16957 votes for William Strong and 16874 votes for Charles Rich.

The National Intelligencer (Washington, DC), November 5, reports 17725 votes for Chauncey Langdon, 17718 votes for Asa Lyon, 17719 votes for Charles Marsh, 17716 votes for Daniel Chipman, 17593 votes for John Noyes, 17665 votes for Luther Jewitt, 16975 votes for Ezra Butler, 16974 votes for Richard Skinner, 16918 votes for William C. Bradley, 16969 votes for James Fisk, 16957 votes for William Strong and 16874 votes for Charles Rich.

The Watchman (Montpelier, VT), October 20: "The committee appointed to count the votes for Members of Congress, from this State, reported the election, by the freemen, of CHAUNCY LANGDON, DANIEL CHIPMAN, ASA LYON, LUTHER JEWETT, CHARLES MARSH, and JOHN NOYES, Esqrs. to represent the State of Vermont for the term of two years from and after the third day of March next in the Congress of the United States."

Columbian Centinel. Massachusetts Federalist (Boston, MA), October 29: "The following return of votes for Representatives to the 14th Congress, in Vermont, is demonstration of the steady and certain convalescence of that important state, which we trust, to use the dignified language of its Legislators in answer to Gov. CHITTENDEN's speech, 'will hold a high rank among those who are taking the lead in the indispensable reformation of our national affairs.'"
